! In probability theory, the birthday problem, or birthday paradox This is
! not a paradox in the sense of leading to a logical contradiction, but is
! called a paradox because the mathematical truth contradicts naïve
! intuition: most people estimate that the chance is much lower than 50%.
! pertains to the probability that in a set of randomly chosen people some
! pair of them will have the same birthday. In a group of at least 23
! randomly chosen people, there is more than 50% probability that some
! pair of them will both have been born on the same day. For 57 or more
! people, the probability is more than 99%, and it reaches 100% when the
! number of people reaches 366 (by the pigeon hole principle, ignoring
! leap years). The mathematics behind this problem leads to a well-known
! cryptographic attack called the birthday attack.
! 
